Exploring London's EU Referendum Vote through Ward based Census Data and Election Results

Notebook created in April 2017

Part 1 - Machine Learning Analysis Workflow with Sci Kit Learn

Background

With the recent calling of a snap uk election and last year's EU Referendum result still dominating discussion, it might be interesting to explore London's EU Ref Voting Preference through Census Data and its past electoral track record, as a means of trying out and illustrating some elementary aspects of data science analysis and the machine learning tools provided by the scikit python library.

In London 2.2 million people voted for Remain and 1.5 million voted to Leave the European Union. Nationally 17,410,742 voted for Leave and 16,141,241 to Remain. This translates to a win of 51.9 % over 48.1% of the 46,500,001 total electorate - 72.2% of which turned out (Source: The Electoral Commision). Given this slim margin and the fact that approximately 2/3rds of Londoners differed from the National Vote we would like to look at some of the characterstics that might explain London's role in this case of a National Split Political Identity.

Questions: What Ward Profile characteristics behind the London EU Vote? How does this relate to London's past Voting Record or Political Party Preferences?

Our starting point was a recent analysis published on the BBC, where Ward based breakdowns of the EU Referendum Vote had been collected from Local Councils via Freedom of Information Requests.

It identified several characterstics of the Remain and Leave Camp, including:

"The combination of education, age and ethnicity accounts for the large majority of the variation in votes between different places"

We will look at whether this relationship also applies to London as portrayed in its Census Profile and Election Result Data.

Method

We will go through the steps of Data Preparation, Initial Cluster Analysis/Visualisation and then onto building a Classification Model following the main stages of Workflow Analysis:

  • Standardisation
  • Pre Processing
  • Reorganisation
  • Model Build
  • Model Evaluation and Visualisation

Key:

precision

Precision is the ability of a classiifer not to label an instance positive that is actually negative. For each class it is defined as as the ratio of true positives to the sum of true and false positives. Said another way, for all instances classified positive, what percent was correct?

recall

Recall is the ability of a classifier to find all positive instances. For each class it is defined as the ratio of true positives to the sum of true positives and false negatives. Said another way, for all instances that were actually positive, what percent was classified correctly?

f1 score

The F1 score is a weighted harmonic mean of precision and recall such that the best score is 1.0 and the worst is 0.0. Generally speaking, F1 scores are lower than accuracy measures as they embed precision and recall into their computation. As a rule of thumb, the weighted average of F1 should be used to compare classifier models, not global accuracy.

support

Support is the number of actual occurrences of the class in the specified dataset. Imbalanced support in the training data may indicate structural weaknesses in the reported scores of the classifier and could indicate the need for stratified sampling or rebalancing. Support doesnt change between models but instead diagnoses the evaluation process.

Precision, Recall or f1 Score:

https://towardsdatascience.com/accuracy-precision-recall-or-f1-331fb37c5cb9`

  • We are aiming for our independent variables to explain as many wards as possible to confirm/deviate from the bcc analysis narrative. Support figures are of concern. We could use f1 score for the model comparison aspect of this workbook.

Recursive Feature Elimination:

Recursively removes features, builds a model using the remaining attributes and calculates model accuracy. RFE is able to work out the combination of attributes that contribute to the prediction on the target variable (or class).

In[]:

Conclusion

Given the close call of the EU Referendum result and with June's Snap General Election looming it will be interesting to see whether Voters vote along Party Lines or if there is a move towards a more "Issues Related" focus by the electorate. With most parties all still supporting some form of Brexit, how do the 48% of Remainers feel and how will they vote? As the Campaign trail gathers momentum, what seats and issues will opposition parties focus their attentions on, and how will the Electorate respond to this Summer's call to vote?

The relative success(in terms of prediction accuracy) displayed by this limited model's tentative brush with the ML reservoirs of Python and Scikit, to some extent, hints at how insight on these and related questions can be gained from in depth examination of the Census Data.
